Software Development (They branch into General Software Development and Game development) 2. Graphic Design 3. IT Security 4. Data Data is actually the least popular one because regarded Game Dev and IT Security (aka hacker wannabes) as the "cool kid" jobs. While graphic design is the general path for anyone since it doesn't involve much or any coding. Data is seen as this boring desk job of looking at mountains of tables and spreadsheet apparently, only recently that we got lots of new students who's actually prefer data because they see it as an easy get-rich career path (thanks to numerous data scientist bloggers telling their success story online lol).  Notes: Basically people in the same class year as me are mostly joining IT for the hype that "easier to get a job as an IT" or the "anti-mainstream" bs. text: Luke, thank YOU for the inspiration and teaching you provide to your subscribers/students with every video you publish! I'm currently finishing Course 6 in the Google Data Analytics Certification (aka The Tableau Data Visualization section). I started DataCamp's SQL Fundamentals Track about two weeks ago for two reasons: (1) I didn't want to lose the SQL knowledge I worked hard to learn in Courses 3-5. I have a family relative who is a data scientist, and he reinforced the importance of SQL skills in a data science career. 90% of the real, daily, and unglorified work of a data science professional is the processing, the cleaning, and the preparation of the data in SQL BEFORE analysis (whether it's in R, Power BI, or Python).
